body:
When building with `python setup.py build_Ext -i`, the build fails at two points. This happens because `HashTable` and `Heap` are typedef-ed twice (once in the header file, once in the source file). Depending on your compiler and C standard you're using, this may cause the compilation to fail.
There is a thread on a similar issue [here](http://code.google.com/p/pycparser/issues/detail?id=70), with links for those curious about more details.

It's an easy fix, as `git diff` can show:

```
diff --git a/libImaging/QuantHash.c b/libImaging/QuantHash.c
index 58d8813..b2bdb06 100644
--- a/libImaging/QuantHash.c
+++ b/libImaging/QuantHash.c
@@ -29,7 +29,7 @@ typedef struct _HashNode {
    HashVal_t value;
 } HashNode;

-typedef struct _HashTable {
+struct _HashTable {
    HashNode **table;
    uint32_t length;
    uint32_t count;
@@ -38,7 +38,7 @@ typedef struct _HashTable {
    KeyDestroyFunc keyDestroyFunc;
    ValDestroyFunc valDestroyFunc;
    void *userData;
-} HashTable;
+};

 #define MIN_LENGTH 11
 #define RESIZE_FACTOR 3
diff --git a/libImaging/QuantHeap.c b/libImaging/QuantHeap.c
index bddcf14..20379ac 100644
--- a/libImaging/QuantHeap.c
+++ b/libImaging/QuantHeap.c
@@ -23,12 +23,12 @@

 #include "QuantHeap.h"

-typedef struct _Heap {
+struct _Heap {
    void **heap;
    int heapsize;
    int heapcount;
    HeapCmpFunc cf;
-} Heap;
+};

 #define INITIAL_SIZE 256
```

This should compile for any compiler.

I'd also be happy to turn this into a pull request if preferred.
